stylometry: The data mining method we used in class was clustering. We took raw data from cities such as socioeconomic status and ethnic percentages and standardized them (using mu and the standard deviation). Then we squared thier distances of each data set to the four cluster centers we chose (to start these could be anything). Then we got the minimum value for reach set and used VLOOKUP to provide which cluster center there were closest to. Then solver is run to make sure you have the right four cluster centers trying to find the minimum value of the squared distance away. This will give you your cluster centers. Each city is then put in a cluster with whichever of the four cluster centers it is most like statistically. For example San Fransisco was clustered with a city that I cannot recall because it had the same general socioeconomic status. Atlanta was clustered with a different city that had the same ethnic percentages. Data mining is great for looking for trends and things that are a like. I ran data mining for the NCAA tournament women's bracket. I had 16 clusters and had about 11 different data points for each of the 64 total teams in the tournament (FG%, blks, ppg, rebounds, etc.) I standardized the data, chose 16 teams to start the clustering with, found the distance between their centers and every statistical data point for all 16 clusters, and then found the minimum value to discover which teams were most alike. I ran solver to get the 16 cluster centers and then found which teams were alike in the NCAA tournament.
